Next condition:
```tactics
constructor
¬∑ -- Show Y' % p = (X^2 - Y^2) % p
  simp [add]
  <;> try { native_decide }
  <;> try { tauto }
```
This proves the second condition. `simp [add]` simplifies `(add q q).Y` to `q.X^2 - q.Y^2`. Then `native_decide` proves `(q.X^2 - q.Y^2) % p = (q.X^2 - q.Y^2) % p`.

Next condition:
```tactics
constructor
¬∑ -- Show Z' % p = (Z^2) % p
  simp [add]
  <;> try { native_decide }
  <;> try { tauto }
```
This proves the third condition. `simp [add]` simplifies `(add q q).Z` to `q.Z^2`. `native_decide` proves `(q.Z^2) % p = (q.Z^2) % p`.

Last condition:
```tactics
¬∑ -- Show T' % p = (T^2) % p
  simp [add]
  <;> try { native_decide }
  <;> try { tauto }
```
This proves the fourth condition. `simp [add]` simplifies `(add q q).T` to `q.T^2`. `native_decide` proves `(q.T^2) % p = (q.T^2) % p`.

The bounds `h_qX_bounds`, `h_qY_bounds`, `h_qZ_bounds` are not used in this proof because the conditions are purely algebraic consequences of the definitions of `add` and the coordinates, and do not depend on the specific bounds. The `native_decide` tactic is powerful enough to prove these trivial equalities once the expressions are simplified.

